	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Few ACP countries benefit from coffee price surge</h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Coffee prices in general have risen to their highest levels since the mid-1990s, according to the latest data from the International Coffee Organisation (ICO). However, detailed figures indicate a wide variation in the gains between ACP countries, due to an ever growing gap between prices for the arabica and robusta varieties of coffee.</p><p>In November the ICO’s monthly Composite Indicator Price – an average of physically traded prices for all grades of coffee – increased by 7.6% to 173.90 US cents per pound (c/lb). This was the highest since July-October 1994, except for one month in 1997. In September 1994 the Composite Indicator reached 202.39 c/lb.</p><p>On 9 November, prices for arabica ‘C’ coffee futures on the New York Intercontinental Exchange (ICE) reached nearly 220 c/lb and remained above $2 for the rest of the month. On 3 December, New York ‘C’ coffee stood at 204.80 c/lb. This pushed prices in the physical trade higher than during the 2008 commodities boom, with Colombian mild arabicas at 244.02 c/lb in November, according to the ICO.</p><p>However, prices in London robusta coffee futures remained well below most of 2008, and this too is reflected in physical trade. The ICO’s robusta composite price increased by 7.9% in November to 92.04 c/lb. By contrast, in March 2008 it stood at 121.92 c/lb, and in September 1994 it reached 182.78 c/lb, or twice recent levels.</p><p>Paradoxically, other ICO data point to a substantial decline in robusta exports over the last year, while arabica exports were on the whole more stable. Between November 2009 and October 2010, worldwide robusta exports were 31.78 million 60 kg bags, some 12% less than the 36.05 million bags exported a year previously. Normally, a shortfall of this size would be expected to push prices sharply up.</p><p>However, over the same period arabica exports increased marginally to 61.79 million bags from 61.76 million.</p><p>Among ACP countries, the biggest beneficiary of the surge in arabica prices was Ethiopia, which produces high-quality arabica and overtook Uganda to become the largest coffee exporter in the ACP group, as its exports increased by 68.5% to 3.03 million bags in the year to October 2010.</p><p>Exports from Uganda, which mostly produces robusta coffee, declined by 13.5% to 2.66 million bags. Another country affected by robusta prices is Côte d’Ivoire, but its robusta exports increased 22% to 2.04 million bags over the same period.</p><p>In total, of the 26 ACP countries listed by the ICO as coffee exporters, 16 are shown as exporting the robusta variety and 15 the arabica variety. Five ACP countries (Cameroon, DR Congo, Papua New Guinea, Tanzania and Uganda) export both arabica and robusta.</p><p>The different price trends are largely explained by differences between the New York and London exchanges where the futures are traded. The New York ‘C’ coffee contract is based on the ‘Colombian mild’ form of arabica, which has been affected by two factors. Total exports of Colombian milds fell 16.3% to 8.12 million bags in the year to October 2010, mainly due to drought and coffee tree renovation in Colombia itself. However, Colombia’s production is recovering now.</p><p>Cameroon’s arabica exports meanwhile dropped to zero in October from 126 tonnes a year previously, apparently due to heavy rains, according to the Bloomberg news agency.</p><p>A second factor on the New York market was a wave of purchases by ‘index investment funds’, which were attracted to arabica coffee by its already rising prices. These funds have bought heavily into commodities in general since the middle of 2010.</p><p>The robusta futures market in London is smaller than New York arabica and has been subject to different influences. Robusta futures prices were marked down by speculative hedge funds for two years until June 2010. More recently there have been concerns over increased supply from Vietnam, the dominant producer of robusta.</p>
		
		
