				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The different patterns of arabica and robusta coffee prices reflect changes in the balance between the two varieties over many years. When coffee prices were at their highest, in the late 1970s, there was little difference in price. Thus, the highest monthly averages recorded by the ICO were 314.96 c/lb for its Composite Indicator, 312.24 c/lb for robusta and 320.78 c/lb for Colombian mild arabicas. All of these were in April 1977.</p><p>By contrast, the ICO’s price for robusta in November 2010 stood at just 53% of the Composite Indicator Price in that month and 38% of that for Colombian milds.</p><p>The growing gap between arabica and robusta prices reflects changes in both demand and supply. Demand for arabica coffee beans has increased as they are generally considered to be of higher quality. Robusta, used mostly for instant coffee, is on the decline.</p><p>Meanwhile, the coffee market has still to absorb the shock caused by Vietnam’s sudden appearance as a major producer of robusta in the late 1990s. Vietnamese coffee production is now second in the world, exceeded only by Brazil’s.</p><p>Arabica-producing ACP countries benefit from these changes, especially those which produce the highest-quality arabicas like Kenya and Ethiopia. Papua New Guinea, Tanzania and Uganda are also significant arabica producers.</p><p>On the other hand, many ACP countries have specialised in growing robusta coffee. They came under pressure when they could not match the scale of Vietnamese output or remain competitive under weak robusta prices. Many of these countries have left the coffee market, the latest being Benin, the Republic of Congo and Nigeria, according to ICO data.</p><p>Numerous ACP countries supplying arabica coffee have also seen production falling, for similar reasons of scale and remoteness from global markets.</p>
		</div>
		
